<p>
  FAND is a national balance-sheet framework: what a country owns, what it
  owes, and the trust infrastructure in between. It is organized in three
  layers &mdash; an aggregate balance sheet, the component items behind it,
  and the transactions that change those items over time.
</p>

<h2>Structure: balance sheet, items, transactions</h2>
<p>
  The <strong>balance sheet</strong> is a single bottom-line figure, Net
  Worth. The <strong>items</strong> are its components: produced assets,
  natural capital, human resources, and substantive rights. The
  <strong>transactions</strong> are the flows &mdash; production, spending,
  income &mdash; that change those components over time.
</p>

<h2>Stocks and flows</h2>
<p>
  FAND separates what can be measured at a point in time from what only
  makes sense over a period. A <strong>stock</strong> &mdash; a building, a
  forest, a population count &mdash; belongs to the balance sheet. A
  <strong>flow</strong> &mdash; production, spending, service delivery
  &mdash; belongs to the transactions side. A small number of stocks, human
  resources foremost, cannot be observed directly and are instead modeled;
  these modeled figures are labeled as such, so it is always clear which
  numbers are observed and which are estimated.
</p>

<h2>Recognition and valuation, kept separate</h2>
<p>
  FAND recognizes broadly: it acknowledges that something exists and
  matters whenever measurement or debate about it exists. Valuation &mdash;
  assigning it a worth &mdash; is a separate, later step, and is
  deliberately left to the people whose values are being measured rather
  than decided by the act of measurement itself. A component that is
  recognized but not yet priced is treated as awaiting valuation, not as
  worth zero.
</p>

<h2 id="identity">The identity</h2>
<p>
  Every entity on the site &mdash; world, country, state, county, block
  group &mdash; resolves the same identity. Worked here on the United
  States, per person, 2025:
</p>
<pre>CW = PA + NC + HR + SR &minus; DM        Commonwealth &mdash; the productive base
NW = CW + CBA &minus; CBL                Net Worth &mdash; adds cross-border claim-rights, nets duties</pre>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Produced Assets (PA)</strong> &mdash; $244,619 &mdash; roads, plant, housing, machines</li>
  <li><strong>Natural Capital (NC)</strong> &mdash; $14,258 &mdash; severable claim-rights: fuels, minerals, timber, farmland</li>
  <li><strong>Human Resources (HR)</strong> &mdash; $410,547 &mdash; the capitalized productive value of people</li>
  <li><strong>Substantive Rights (SR)</strong> &mdash; $750,927 &mdash; trust infrastructure not counted elsewhere; the largest single line</li>
  <li><strong>Cross-border claim-rights (CBA)</strong> &mdash; $62,768 &mdash; foreign assets residents hold</li>
  <li><em>(less)</em> cross-border duties and upkeep (CBL) &mdash; &minus;$89,174</li>
  <li><strong>Net Worth (NW) &mdash; $1,384,850</strong></li>
</ul>

<h2>Why GDP misses part of the picture</h2>
<p>
  National accounting standards recognize only one category of legal
  relationship identified by the legal scholar Wesley Hohfeld: claim-rights
  and their corresponding duties. Categories such as liberty, power, and
  immunity &mdash; a person's freedom to use their own time, or their
  standing to participate in governance &mdash; fall outside that
  accounting boundary and are, by omission, valued at zero. Substantive
  Rights is the FAND component built to capture what these accounts leave
  out.
</p>

